===Verb===
{{en-verb|underwrites|underwriting|underwrote|underwritten}}

{{rfex|en}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To write below or under; [[subscribe]].
# {{lb|en|transitive|intransitive|obsolete}} To [[subscribe]] (a document, policy etc.) with one's name.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[sign]]; to put one's name to.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To agree to pay by signing one's name; subscribe.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} Specifically, to [[assume]] [[financial]] [[responsibility]] for something, and [[guarantee]] it against [[failure]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1962|month=October|title=Talking of Trains: Passed to you, Mr. Macmillan|journal=Modern Railways|page=220|text=Dr. Beeching's obvious intent is that if Scottish&mdash;and similarly unprofitable English and Welsh&mdash;railways are to be maintained, it must be done by an unconcealed subsidy; he is determined that the railways shall no longer be preoccupied with&mdash;and derided for&mdash;immense deficits which include the burden of social services the State must openly '''underwrite''', if it wants them.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|insurance}} To act as an [[underwriter]].
#* '''1810''', Samuel Marshall, ''Of marine insurance''
#*: The broker who procures the insurance {{...}}ought not, by '''underwriting''' the policy, to deprive the parties of his unbiased testimony.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[support]], lend support to, guarantee the basis of.
# {{lb|en|obsolete|transitive}} To [[submit]] to; [[put up with]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Troilus|2|3|passage=Disguise the holy strength of their command, <br>And '''underwrite''' in an observing kind}}

